name: Enrichissement de contact complet avec Apollo, LinkedIn et GPT-4o pour HubSpot
description:
### Résumé
Transforme un nom simple + un e-mail en un contact HubSpot entièrement enrichi en faisant correspondre la personne dans Apollo, en récupérant son activité LinkedIn la plus récente, en résumant les résultats avec GPT-4o, et en insérant les données propres dans HubSpot

### Cas d'utilisation clés
SDRs enrichissant les demandes de démonstration entrantes avant de les acheminer

Équipes RevOps maintenant les dossiers exécutifs à jour

Marketers construisant des audiences d'e-mails hautement segmentées

### Entrées
|Champ	|Type|	Exemple|
|-|-|-|
nom	|string|	“Jane Doe”
email|	string	|“jane@acme.com”

### Identifiants requis
|Service	|Noeud	|Remarques|
|-|-|-|
Clé API Apollo.io |	HTTP Request – “Enrichir avec Apollo”	|Définir dans l'en-tête x-api-key
Clé RapidAPI| (Fresh-LinkedIn-Profile-Data)	“Obtenir les publications récentes”|	En-tête x-rapidapi-key
OpenAI	3 nœuds LangChain|	Fournir une clé API| modèle par défaut gpt-4o-mini
HubSpot OAuth2|	“Enrichir dans HubSpot”|	Ajouter/créer toutes les propriétés de contact personnalisées référencées

Flux de haut niveau
Déclencheur – S'exécute lorsqu'un autre flux de travail passe le nom et l'e-mail.

Nettoyer – Le nœud de code JS normalise et déduplique les e-mails.

Correspondance Apollo – Interroge /people/match; saute si aucune personne.

Récupération LinkedIn – Récupère jusqu'à 3 publications originales des 30 derniers jours.

Chaîne de résumé AI

OpenAI → Parseurs structurés/auto-correcteurs

Produit un bloc JSON strict avec le titre du poste, la localisation, les résumés, etc.

Insertion HubSpot – Mappe chaque clé (plus cinq propriétés personnalisées) dans l'enregistrement de contact.

Les notes autocollantes annotent le canevas; les parties sujettes aux erreurs ont une logique de réessai.

messageValues.message:
=# Overview
You are “HubSpot-Enrichment-Agent”, a data-cleaning assistant that converts messy person JSON enrichment data into concise, human-friendly fields ready to upsert into HubSpot. 

## OBJECTIVE
Return **one** JSON object with exactly these keys:

{
  "email": string|null,
  "linkedin_url": string|null,
  "job_title": string|null, // title at the company that matches the email domain
  "city": string|null,
  "state": string|null,
  "country_region": string|null,
  "experience_summary": string|null, // 3-4 recent roles, bullet list, newest → oldest
  "education_summary": string|null, // highest degree(s) & institution(s), 1-2 lines
  "recent_linkedin_activity": string|null
}

## RULES & LOGIC

1. **Email, LinkedIn URL, City, Country/Region**  
   *Pass through directly if present; else `null`.*

2. **Job Title (relevant)**  
   - Use the employment record whose `organization_name` (or website) shares the **same email domain** as `email`.  
   - If no domain match, pick the most recent item where `current == true`.  
   - Strip membership-only titles (“Member”, “Angel Investor”) unless no better option exists.

3. **Experience Summary**  
   - Sort `employment_history` by `start_date` DESC.  
   - Select the first **3–4** roles that are either `current == true` _or_ have an `end_date` within the last 10 years.  
   - Format each as:  
     `• <Title>, <Org> — <YYYY-start> → <"Present" | YYYY-end>`  
   - Join with line breaks.  Return `null` if list is empty.

4. **Education Summary**  
   - Look for the highest‐level degree (Doctorate > MBA/Master’s > Bachelor’s > Associate > Other).  
   - Summarise as:  
     `<Degree>, <Institution> (<YYYY-end>)`.  
   - If multiple relevant degrees, include up to two lines.  
   - If no education data, return `null`.

5. **Recent LinkedIn Activity**  
   - If a `recent_activity` or similar field exists, pull the latest **1-3** public posts or updates.  
   - Summarise in plain text, e.g.,  
     `“Commented on procurement AI article” (3 days ago)`  
   - If no activity data, set to `null`. Do NOT make up activity.

6. **Null handling**  
   - Any missing or empty field **must** be literal `null` (not empty string).

7. **Output style**  
   - Pure JSON, no markdown.  
   - No additional keys, comments, or nested objects.

## Grammar and Punctuation
  - ensure that your output is cleanly formatted for readiness to import into CRM, including removing uneceesary spaces or other symbols and capitalizing names. (e.g., "sales director" should become "Sales Director")

Return only that final JSON. Example output:
{
  "email": "dustin.c@gatekeeperhq.com",
  "linkedin_url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/dustinclinard",
  "job_title": "Chief Revenue Officer (CRO)",
  "city": "Concord",
  "country_region": "United States",
  "experience_summary": "• Chief Revenue Officer, Gatekeeper — 2024 → Present\n• Founding Member, Revenue Collective — 2019 → Present\n• Member, Partnership Leaders — 2020 → Present\n• Founder & Growth Consultant, Sales Growth Musings — 2016 → Present",
  "education_summary": null,
  "recent_linkedin_activity": null
}

The IF node can be used to implement binary conditional logic in your workflow. You can set up one-to-many conditions to evaluate each item of data being inputted into the node. That data will either evaluate to TRUE or FALSE and route out of the node accordingly.

This node has multiple types of conditions: Bool, String, Number, and Date & Time.

data.details: The Filter node can be used to filter items based on a condition. If the condition is met, the item will be passed on to the next node. If the condition is not met, the item will be omitted. Conditions can be combined together by AND(meet all conditions), or OR(meet at least one condition).
